        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "DOMAIN",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Alpha chains of type IV collagen have a non-collagenous domain (NC1) at their C-terminus, frequent interruptions of the G-X-Y repeats in the long central triple-helical domain (which may cause flexibility in the triple helix), and a short N-terminal triple-helical 7S domain"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "SUBCELLULAR LOCATION",
          "subcellularLocations": [
            {
              "location": {
                "value": "Secreted, extracellular space, extracellular matrix, basement membrane"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "PTM",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Prolines at the third position of the tripeptide repeating unit (G-X-Y) are hydroxylated in some or all of the chains"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "PTM",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Type IV collagens contain numerous cysteine residues which are involved in inter- and intramolecular disulfide bonding. 12 of these, located in the NC1 domain, are conserved in all known type IV collagens"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "SIMILARITY",
          "texts": [
